4.0 of 5 bubbles
Ha Long Bay-What are Must See? Must Do? What to skip?
Jan 2015 ‚Ä¢ Couples
Must see, must do‚ÄîJunk Boat tour. I would do 2 nights. The reasons are:
1) Fog is prevalent in the Bay. Fortunately, the fog lifted during the afternoon on our first day. Our breath was taken away by the sheer beauty of this natural wonder. We watched sunset. Not so lucky on our second day. Fog covered the beauty most of the second day. We met tourists who chose 1-night package. They never saw the beauty we did. 2-nights package provided one extra daylight opportunity to see and be in awe of the beauty.
2) The 2-night tour also includes a kayak tour, which I think for me is the most memorable and enjoyable part of this tour. Why this is worth the trip alone? We were able to enter parts of the bay only allowed by kayaks; which means no Junk Boats, no rusty tankers, no house boats, and significantly-reduced debris. My most favorite part is this tiny tiny bay, reachable only through these tunnels, formed by these magnificent limestone islands. This tiny bay was serene, perfectly still. The water is clear, and vibrant emerald. The sky, the surrounding islands harmoniously blend to a perfect painting imprinted in my mind forever. At the bay, I was able to go beyond intellectually what it means to be connected to heaven, earth. I was able to be immersed into this beauty, nature, all blended into one. This is what the trip experience is about. This is what life is about.
3) Third reason is two-day tour include a visit to the cave. This natural formation is a wonder to see. The vastness of the cave is deceiving from the outside. The crowd is something to get used to. But it is definitely worth a visit.
Just in case you wonder about 3 nights or more as I did, it was not recommended or encouraged. The junk boats and tour guide just recycle the same route, same itinerary, same activities, same performances, same food.
Bring a light jacket, a scarf for evening chill. We were there in January, and the jackets & scarves were needed. Hat, swim wear, water shoes, walking shoes (for the cave), sunglasses, all come in handy.
What to Skip:
I would skip swimming in the Bay. Even though the tour guides encourage jumping into this gorgeous emerald water, I would think twice. Swimming may be a wonderful idea 10-15 years ago. If you pay attention to the activities on the water, by the junk boats, by the tankers, by the locals who live full-time on their boats, you may come to the same conclusion. The lack of environmental awareness and weak enforcement to protect this precious bay gave me plenty of reasons to skip swimming.
If you are travelling without a driver or a guide, I would skip most of the ‚Äúmanufacturers‚Äù or ‚Äúfarms‚Äù unless you need a washroom break. I was told the tour drivers must have at least one break. And the drivers usually stop at one of these factories. It serves 2 purposes: 1 is the drivers get fed at these facilities. The second purpose is to have their passengers make some purchases. As in everywhere in Vietnam, price is negotiable, even if they tell you no. I don‚Äôt mean to be prejudice or to offend anyone. The truth is if your outer appearance is westerner, (fair skin, blond hair), the asking price tend to be much higher. Value is in the eye of the beholder. Just ‚Äúbuyer beware. ‚Äú
One final personal note:
Ha Long Bay, don‚Äôt expect perfection, as shown in many tourist pictures. The thousands of limestone islands sprinkled around this emerald water are real. Junk boats are also real. However, what is not revealed is the number of junk boats scattered around the Bay.
For me, the most disturbing part of the Ha Long Bay is the lack of respect for this precious precious nature! Debris such as plastic bottles, foam items, houseware, even life jackets, scattered throughout this beautiful emerald water. I was told by our junk boat guide, the government does hire local boaters to collect garbage off the water. Not enough of them.
Coming from beautiful BC where natural environment is so sacred, and precious, and fervently protected, I was horrified!
In addition to the debris, it was also impossible to ignore huge rusty tankers in the midst of this amazing vast beauty! We could get close to one tanker and observed black materials (coal?) being loaded onto primitive tiny row boats, operated by single individuals. I assume it is to transport to shore? I saw no patrols, no monitoring, of any sort.
Having said all that, Yes, Ha Long Bay is definitely worth experiencing. There are many tour / junk boat operators. I suggest to go with 4 star & up.
Background: Husband and wife in 50's -60's. Wife who does not swim, loved the kayaking, as mentioned in the review. Don't miss it!
Written October 8, 2015
